    <section class="faq-sec">
      <h2>Gummies vs Pills — Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Are gummy supplements as effective as pills?</summary><p>For most ingredients, yes. Clinical studies show no significant bioavailability difference for vitamins D, B12, C, melatonin, and many other nutrients when doses are equivalent. The key factor is dose per serving — some gummies contain less active ingredient than pill equivalents.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Do gummies absorb better than pills?</summary><p>Gummies may have a slight absorption edge because chewing begins digestion in the mouth. However, the difference is modest for most nutrients. Pills with enteric coatings may be superior for acid-sensitive ingredients like probiotics.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Why are gummy supplements more expensive?</summary><p>Gummy manufacturing involves complex flavor development, pectin or gelatin formulation, and specialized equipment. Gummies also have shorter shelf life, increasing costs. The typical premium is 2-5x compared to equivalent pills.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Do gummy vitamins contain too much sugar?</summary><p>Most contain 2-4 grams per serving (8-16 calories) — nutritionally insignificant. Sugar-free options using stevia, monk fruit, or allulose are widely available. The compliance benefit typically outweighs the minimal sugar content.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Which supplements work better as pills?</summary><p>Iron, calcium, and high-dose omega-3 fish oil are better as pills. Iron has a metallic taste difficult to mask. Calcium requires large doses impractical in gummy form. Fish oil has stability and taste issues as gummies.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Which supplements work better as gummies?</summary><p>Melatonin, vitamin D, vitamin C, elderberry, ashwagandha, and B12 are excellent in gummy form. These can be accurately dosed, taste good, and melatonin may work faster through sublingual absorption.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Are gummies safe for children?</summary><p>Child-formulated gummies are generally safe when taken as directed. However, their candy-like appearance creates overconsumption risk. Store out of reach of children. Iron-containing gummies are of particular concern — iron overdose is the leading cause of poisoning deaths in children under 6.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Do gummy supplements expire faster than pills?</summary><p>Yes. Gummies last 12-18 months versus 24-36 months for pills. Moisture content accelerates degradation, especially for probiotics and B-vitamins. Store in a cool, dry place and check expiration dates.</p></details>
    </section>

  </div>

  <div class="cta">
    <h2>Find the Best Gummy Supplements</h2>
    <p>Browse our expert-tested guides across every category. Over 200 products reviewed by registered dietitians.</p>
